Drilling and preterm birth, case-control study

David J.X. Gonzalez

This document summarizes data and findings from the study, Oil and gas drilling and risk of spontaneous preterm birth in the San Joaquin Valley, California, by David J.X. Gonzalez, Allison R. Sherris, Wei Yang, Amy Padula, David K. Stevenson, Michael Baiocchi, Mark R. Cullen, and Gary M. Shaw.

1 Project Summary

Prior studies report an association between adverse birth outcomes, including preterm birth, and maternal proximity to oil and gas wells. These studies have not accounted for exposure to conventional oil and gas drilling operations. Our objective was to determine whether maternal residence proximity to oil and gas drilling activity increases odds of preterm birth. We conducted a case-control study using data from 27,913 preterm births and 197,461 term births between 1999 and 2012 in the San Joaquin Valley, California. We obtained births data from the Office of Statewide Health Planning and Development (OSHPD) and wells data from the California Department of Conservation, Division of . For each birth, we computed an exposure index by taking the sum of the inverse distance to all oil and gas drilling activity within a 15 km radius of the maternal residence. We defined four preterm birth categories based on gestational length (in weeks): 20-23, 24-27, 28-31, and 32-36. We estimate crude and adjusted odds ratios for preterm birth in each category using logistic regression. Results [see ISEE abstract] Discussion [see ISEE abstract]

2 Methods

Project Workflow

  1. Gather data from California on (a) births from OSHPD and (b) oil and gas wells from DOGGR
  2. Prepare data for analyses
  3. For each birth and each month of gestation (B1-P10), assess exposure to wells by generating an exposure index inverse distance squared weighting
  4. Divide exposure into categories: no exposure, and exposure tertiles
  5. Conduct primary analyses using logistic regression models to assess the association between preterm birth and exposure; compare most births (highest tertile) to unexposed births; includes unadjusted models; models adjusted for observed maternal covariates; and models adjusted for observed maternal covariates and birth yearr
  6. Conduct sensitivity analyses
  1. Test assumptions in the exposure assessment
  2. Stratify on observed maternal covariates
  3. Consider exposure by trimester
  4. Assess association between preterm birth and exposure to abandoned wells
  1. Visualize results
  2. Prepare figures and tables for manuscript, as well as supplementary materials

3 Data

3.1 Data Description

Birth Outcomes Data

We constructed a dataset comprising spontaneous preterm birth cases and randomly selected term birth controls, excluding births with maternal comorbidities associated with preterm birth. Inclusion criteria were singleton births delivered after 20 to 41 weeks of gestation and with a birthweight between 500 and 5,000 grams (Figure S1). Of the 771,416 births that fit these criteria, 78,421 were preterm birth cases, defined as delivery at fewer than 37 gestational weeks. For each case, we randomly selected 235,263 term birth controls, in a 3:1 ratio of controls to cases. For all controls and cases, we extracted the residential address at time of birth from the birth certificate. The California Environmental Health Tracking Program Geocoding Service geocoded each address, after standardizing, verifying, and correcting addresses. Geocoding was successful for 221,651 (93%) of controls and 73,736 (94%) of cases.

Next, we linked the cases and controls with discharge data from the Office of Statewide Health and Planning (OSHPD). Linkage was successful for 220,137 (99%) controls and 72,907 (99%) cases. We removed cases where preterm birth may have been medically indicated and excluded births with the following maternal comorbidities, owing to the assumption that their underlying etiologies would be different: pre-gestational diabetes, gestational diabetes, gestational hypertension, preeclampsia/eclampsia, and chronic hypertension (except for the 20 to 23-week group). This resulted in a final dataset comprising 225,374 births, including 27,913 spontaneous preterm cases and 197,461 term controls. Following definitions previously used by Shaw et al. (2018), we divided preterm birth into three categories based on gestational age: 20-27 weeks (very early), 28-31 weeks (early), and 32-36 weeks (moderate).

Oil and Gas Wells Data

We obtained data on oil and gas wells from the California Department of Conservation, Division of Oil, Gas, and Geothermal Resources (DOGGR GIS Unit 2019). The DOGGR dataset includes locations and records for all wells in California and is updated daily. The data used in this study were obtained in April 2018. Records are available for well type, status, and development dates, including date of spudding (initial drilling) and completion (when the well is ready for production). For the purposes of the current study, we compiled a dataset including wells drilled during the study period in the eight study counties plus a 15 km buffer, to account for residences along county borders. We identified 11,972 unique wells that met the above criteria.

4.3.3 Sensitivity C: Stratified on exposure (Trimester 1, 2, 3)

Exposure by trimester
